[{"id":26942,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2609148b-0086-4ce8-a16a-29b12b5ee41b-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e531d14c-6e92-49dc-8d6b-00836c4b8d4c-image.png\" style=\"width: 224px; height: 80px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/09840c42-68af-465b-8e05-bc9063ff89e1-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9615fb4b-3ea0-46cc-9f8f-b9c40a703098-image.png\" style=\"width: 189px; height: 113px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/15ef69b9-0f06-425f-806f-57487f22f9a9-image.png\" style=\"width: 357px; height: 288px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26983,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Aldol condensation","Claisen condensation","Cannizzaro reaction","Pinacol-pinacolon reaction"],"answer":2,"solution":"Tishchenko reaction is a modification of Canizzaro's reaction. This reaction involves disproportionation of an aldehyde lacking a hydrogen atom in the alpha position in the presence of an alkoxide. The reaction product is an ester. Catalysts are aluminium alkoxide or sodium alkoxide.\nIn Cannizzaro's reaction the base is sodium hydroxide and the oxidation product is a carboxylic acid and the reduction product is an alcohol.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/pfqfJzKmz8TigeXzLFw7HIfjVnG79BFQqVLQJgqBTO8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26896,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6dede4c6-cd37-4f09-b0d4-c2e011539fef-image.png\" style=\"width: 205px; height: 70px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/067b5dfb-3203-45b3-804b-9afa830abeb2-image.png\" style=\"width: 93px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1f306b42-575b-445d-a69d-4cb6ed619656-image.png\" style=\"width: 87px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/95ac829b-fb66-4d95-913e-b4484c9f9d54-image.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 80px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In first step of the reaction&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;will attack on the lone pairs of electrons of the oxygen atom. Which will get dehydrated forming carbocation intermediate. On this carbocation&nbsp;pi bond will attack forming a five membered cyclic ring. In last step&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Br</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;will combine with carbocation forming final product according to the following reactions.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7ec1e782-39a9-4689-93cb-7268fa53eda7-image.png\" style=\"width: 461px; height: 300px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26997,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["$2-$ethoxypropane","ethoxypropane","methoxybutane","$2-$methoxybutane"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fum1DWAsVqOe-GzBHUeD7AohwSxfPWq6NsPFIOtnjL4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nhence the IUPAC name of compound is<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/w0fp-voFdRiZYG7yVzU5qIRL5q14xILxfTKT_I_TEhU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26826,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["160","4","88","46"],"answer":3,"solution":"Reaction A: Phenol reacts with metallic sodium to produce sodium phenoxide and hydrogen gas.<br>C₆H₅OH + Na → C₆H₅ONa + ½H₂.<br>The gas evolved is x = H₂ with molar mass 2 g/mol.<br>Reaction B: Benzoic acid reacts with sodium bicarbonate to produce sodium benzoate, water, and carbon dioxide.<br>C₆H₅COOH + NaHCO₃ → C₆H₅COONa + H₂O + CO₂.<br>The gas evolved is y = CO₂ with molar mass 44 g/mol.<br>Therefore, molar mass of x + molar mass of y = 2 + 44 = 46.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26917,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dbbe964a-d901-4ee5-b5ee-c2053b941d33-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 144px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8d5a1feb-68ff-452b-89b0-10315ee0acd5-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 166px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/044a4678-596e-42a9-9be3-ca1339f65c36-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 157px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b1a1c5ca-0ee1-436a-bcd6-bec1bfd237db-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 154px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4c7d25c6-df0e-4c7c-bce3-1a662ab5efcc-image.png\" style=\"width: 498px; height: 238px;\" /><br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2c20cafd-b6b1-4fd3-b4f3-36b7824b0c82-image.png\" style=\"width: 406px; height: 312px;\" /><br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cbec61e7-3936-48b0-bda0-81945054f661-image.png\" style=\"width: 580px; height: 227px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26885,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b3d59e7-2c15-4fd5-ba7d-2804152007a3-9895331_A.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 171px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cd45c397-353f-4969-b389-4431754c880c-9895331_B.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 170px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7ce4e8fe-0bb2-4978-8706-41f69aaf3cab-9895331_C.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 170px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bf3d8f2c-69c2-421d-bce8-1aeaf40e528e-9895331_D.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 115px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>In the first step, alcohol group accepts a proton from the hydronium ion, and thus leaves forming a carbocation. As there is a chance for formation of a six-membered ring, a six membered ring is formed with a carbocation. Hydrogen next to the carbocation leaves forming a cycloalkene which is also the saytzeff product. Chain of reactions are as follows:</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5dc76dec-a96f-4270-a7d9-69af5342196e-969e45db-c6d5-4ace-bc99-d5c20859a8ea-9884748_2.png\" style=\"width: 812px; height: 272px;\" />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26890,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16620c85-d70b-4bf2-9b67-b87f92205744-9894408.PNG\" style=\"width: 124px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c2e82c10-55ae-48b3-b582-7d10c6c87cae-9894408_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 101px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aebae673-e8a4-4106-b222-3f3cc5e98405-9894408_2.PNG\" style=\"width: 85px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f8a1f608-c395-4596-b53b-812f48381658-9894408_3.PNG\" style=\"width: 205px; height: 140px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Cumene&nbsp;(isopropylbenzene) is oxidised in the presence of air to cumene hydroperoxide. It is converted to phenol and acetone by treating it with dilute acid.&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6d5cfc5e-1c45-4f70-a8c9-e2cbff1d2e0b-9894408_4.PNG\" style=\"width: 431px; height: 180px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26982,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Phenolphthalein","Alizarin","Coumarin","Fluorescein"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/BDZ-cAX9sFyKGBKX5M_GnKd0SQ1V94ohODhHhCQBIyI.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_vJF8oN0lJAFtRHMH5LlBBI4hrEGejUwUBHlbsp-_r0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26962,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCHO</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>PhCH</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>MgX</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PhCOCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgX</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>PhMgX</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PhCOCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>MgX</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>&nbsp;The given compound is tertiary alcohol and formaldehyde forms secondary alcohol on reaction with Grignard reagent.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4346e290-a9ff-4491-a02a-b0cd97d28ca0-image.png\" style=\"width: 395px; height: 514px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26851,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6yL2s8WxtZ8Pkixovdij4vs1teXidrIZSb-alKJ5A7E.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26920,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d9dec2c3-e3b2-47d1-8f4f-97451216f8a7-image.png\" style=\"width: 381px; height: 78px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3fe8b50b-a5f0-4547-8468-a29b5ff0aa44-image.png\" style=\"width: 354px; height: 80px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a92c92f9-82d7-4181-8a62-7cdc186e6455-image.png\" style=\"width: 358px; height: 83px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8e200753-b71e-4a67-8984-da7dca3a5383-image.png\" style=\"width: 361px; height: 82px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4d862968-00be-4b34-a7c0-8392633845ea-da04655e-407f-4433-9fa2-fac978ae2781-image.png\" style=\"width: 638px; height: 173px;\" /><br />Alcohol undergoes elimination reaction inpresence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26858,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{B}=1\\)-Propanol \\(\\mathrm{C}=2\\)-Propanol","\\(\\mathrm{B}=\\mathrm{C}=2\\)-Propanol","\\(\\mathrm{B}=2\\)-Propanol \\(\\mathrm{C}=1\\)-Propanol","\\(\\mathrm{B}=\\mathrm{C}=1\\)-Propanol"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qggSBsX394ApgwM29z9FNLVT3IvNCQ5k45vvxUFT9Jo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26944,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Reimer-Tiemann formylation reaction :</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5ecc3aea-b7d8-4bcb-a774-ed451413f9a9-image.png\" style=\"width: 490px; height: 190px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Molecular formula of product is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Percentage weight of carbon<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>84</mn><mn>122</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>68</mn><mo>.85</mo><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26897,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e54f5ca6-b7c2-4b8d-8196-787a02f3ec5b-image.png\" style=\"width: 225px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3893db21-6532-4326-a4e3-0e0bc04ced12-image.png\" style=\"width: 243px; height: 140px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e69fc05d-12ef-4468-8e60-36f77b1d275d-image.png\" style=\"width: 357px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/885297ee-36cd-4c96-b11c-3e467181239e-image.png\" style=\"width: 305px; height: 90px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Alkyl aryl ethers are cleaved at the alkyl-oxygen bond due to the more stable aryl-oxygen bond. The reaction yields phenol and alkyl halide.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12f37d8a-5472-411d-99fc-05d5d72cd52e-9758467_S.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 113px;\" /></p><p>And then&nbsp;Phenol is converted to benzene on heating with zinc dust.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/77a292b5-64f2-473f-b797-ad195fc9a9b7-image.png\" style=\"width: 538px; height: 80px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26812,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":2,"solution":"Step 1: The first reagent is Cu at $573\\text{ K}$. When a tertiary alcohol like tert-butyl alcohol is passed over heated copper at $573\\text{ K}$, it undergoes dehydration rather than dehydrogenation to form an alkene. <br><br>$(CH_3)_3C-OH \\xrightarrow{Cu / 573\\text{ K}} CH_2=C(CH_3)_2 + H_2O$<br>The intermediate product is isobutylene (2-methylpropene).<br><br>Step 2: The second set of reagents is $H^+$ and $PhCOOH$ (benzoic acid). This is an acid-catalyzed addition of a carboxylic acid to an alkene, which is a standard method for synthesizing tert-butyl esters.<br>First, the alkene is protonated by the acid to form the most stable carbocation, which is the tertiary butyl carbocation:<br>$CH_2=C(CH_3)_2 + H^+ \\rightleftharpoons (CH_3)_3C^+$<br><br>Next, the carboxylic acid acts as a nucleophile and attacks the carbocation. The oxygen atom of the benzoic acid attacks the tert-butyl carbocation, followed by deprotonation:<br>$PhCOOH + (CH_3)_3C^+ \\rightleftharpoons Ph-CO-O^+(H)-C(CH_3)_3 \\rightleftharpoons Ph-CO-O-C(CH_3)_3 + H^+$<br><br>The final major product is tert-butyl benzoate. Electrophilic aromatic substitution (Friedel-Crafts alkylation) on the benzene ring does not occur here because the $-COOH$ group is strongly deactivating, making O-alkylation (ester formation) the highly preferred pathway.<br><br>Comparing this with the given options, Option (C) represents the structure of tert-butyl benzoate.<br><br>Answer:","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26863,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Salicyclic acid","Benzene-1,2-diol","Benzene-1, 3-diol","2-Hydroxybenzaldehyde"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Chloroform <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>CHCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced></math> in the presence of an alkali <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>NaOH</mi></mfenced></math> undergoes formylation of phenol at the ortho-position. This is also called as the Reimer-Tiemann reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0c717928-6141-4e90-9e6f-77e61cdc75fb.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 164px;\"/>Hence, the answer is option D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26814,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The chemical reaction of phenol with zinc dust is given by:<br><br>$C_6H_5OH + Zn \\xrightarrow{\\Delta} C_6H_6 + ZnO$<br><br>Product X is benzene ($C_6H_6$).<br><br>Molar mass of phenol ($C_6H_5OH$) = $6 \\times 12 + 6 \\times 1 + 16 = 94$ g mol$^{-1}$<br><br>Number of moles of phenol taken = $\\dfrac{4.7}{94} = 0.05$ mol<br><br>From the stoichiometry of the reaction, 1 mole of phenol produces 1 mole of benzene.<br><br>Theoretical moles of X formed = $0.05$ mol<br><br>Since the reaction goes to $60\\%$ completion, the actual moles of X formed is:<br><br>$0.05 \\times \\dfrac{60}{100} = 0.03$ mol<br><br>This can be written as $3 \\times 10^{-2}$ mol.<br><br>Answer: $3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26986,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["KMnO<sub>4</sub>","K<sub>2</sub>Cr<sub>2</sub>O<sub>7</sub>","CrO<sub>3</sub>","PCC (Pyridinium Chlorochromate)"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&bull; KMnO<sub>4</sub>&nbsp;will&nbsp;oxidize&nbsp;the alcohol to carboxylic acid.<br />&bull;&nbsp;K<sub>2</sub>Cr<sub>2</sub>O<sub>7</sub>&nbsp;will also make carboxylic acids.<br />&bull;&nbsp;​CrO<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;in acetic acid is Jones reagent, it also converts&nbsp;alcohols&nbsp;to carboxylic acid.<br />&bull;​ PCC is a weak oxidising agent. It limits the oxidation to the aldehyde.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27004,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["butanal","$n-$butyl alcohol","$n-$propyl alcohol","propanal"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/i8YJ4bYvihW2xV43gOgfzLrhoOspwbsFXKhaWONzLVU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n$\\therefore$ the compound $\\mathrm{D}$ is $n-$propyl alcohol. \nHence, (C) is correct option.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":26935,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/024c3a53-2ea8-45ce-bb88-206b811a4eaf-image.png\" style=\"width: 367px; height: 247px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27003,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["2,4,6-trinitrobenzene","o-nitrophenol","p-nitrophenol","nitrobenzene"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5PCOiUgX8lFkMw9-IDAL7DWXmrWW4zMqCcBD3lzwMAk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":26900,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2dff6016-eb2e-48b5-94cc-98418fecddec-image.png\" style=\"width: 77px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1615c2f7-a009-4502-8480-04a8fe54a561-image.png\" style=\"width: 77px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/31523117-2c12-4600-aa9a-fee55fe8fbbd-image.png\" style=\"width: 88px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/02841711-fada-4c1f-adc7-1d50bab9f713-image.png\" style=\"width: 88px; height: 150px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Alcohols are more reactive than phenol towards the reaction with hydrogen chloride.&nbsp;The preparation of alkyl iodide from alkyl bromide or chloride with potassium or sodium iodide in acetone is generally known as the Finkelstein reaction.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1ba85a9b-69ea-4ea5-abb0-262d3d3e386e-86fb8eca-cfbc-4503-a8ee-1de1a99d68ce-9756596_S3(1).png\" style=\"width: 438px; height: 414px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26966,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dee591d9-8e2d-42b1-a614-375c69a69c88-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 146px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/56499b6f-bd94-4d0b-95c1-87eb77e64f2c-image.png\" style=\"width: 321px; height: 104px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/02a7cb5c-f060-4ae7-baa1-dabd11a0d1a2-image.png\" style=\"width: 318px; height: 138px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0d6b1152-dc3c-4f80-8e92-3ea73785f867-image.png\" style=\"width: 320px; height: 138px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Cumene is an organic compound obtained by&nbsp;Friedel-Crafts alkylation of benzene with&nbsp;propylene. Upon oxidation of cumene (isopropylbenzene) in the presence of air, cumene hydroperoxide is obtained. Upon further treatment of cumene hydroperoxide with dilute acid, phenols are obtained</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fcf5eb83-62a7-459e-a470-19df030d523f-image.png\" style=\"width: 576px; height: 223px;\" /><br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cfa231b9-ed95-4696-81cd-54f46a97cb65-image.png\" style=\"width: 378px; height: 262px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/10b2e2cd-d7e1-4988-9e43-8b4cbb654e2c-image.png\" style=\"width: 643px; height: 229px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26845,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["(A), (D) and (E) Only","(C), (D) and (E) Only","(A), (C) and (D) Only","(A), (B) and (C) Only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c3C4RM9nifEkrWlmj3bzgzMM3ntx4RNR8pxrrJ30s0I.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\nAll gives positive Fehling test","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26819,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Violet","Green","Red","Colourless"],"answer":3,"solution":"The given reaction sequence represents the synthesis and acid-base behaviour of phenolphthalein.<br><br>When phenol reacts with phthalic anhydride in the presence of concentrated $H_2SO_4$, phenolphthalein is formed. In acidic or neutral medium, phenolphthalein exists in a lactone form which is colourless.<br><br>Upon addition of a moderate amount of alkali (NaOH), the lactone ring opens and a proton is removed, forming a dianion with an extended conjugated quinonoid structure. This extended conjugation is responsible for the characteristic pink colour of phenolphthalein in basic medium.<br><br>When excess NaOH is added (strongly alkaline medium), a hydroxide ion attacks the central $sp^2$ hybridized carbon atom of the quinonoid structure. This converts the central carbon to an $sp^3$ hybridized state, forming a carbinol structure (compound X).<br><br>Because the central carbon is now $sp^3$ hybridized, the extended conjugation is broken. As a result, the compound loses its colour and becomes colourless.<br><br>Therefore, compound X is colourless.<br><br>Answer: Colourless","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26988,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nlF6zK1PqE7EQ7DlFgZYNDqzQppqSJdPZNw82EZxKXY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ePAQFeUWjni694d6PRS2Cvi3i9odiEQ7N3UF95hqyEI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/mRJqVMEwM0ChyQaKiw-z6lcmSSDbx01SSHX8VF8iwko.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hZ06KNyffrSBtes5hnjc64P9bwrNOMErRGbKm6Fl2ZY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26941,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/72c8b7e3-b05a-4ea3-9e03-42521f22a918-image.png\" style=\"width: 114px; height: 127px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d049873f-3a47-47e5-85ad-b60a5d637441-image.png\" style=\"width: 114px; height: 128px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f3be53c3-2fde-4067-aa72-bf34f39de434-image.png\" style=\"width: 114px; height: 127px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6379f821-f063-4abc-823f-096db5c5a194-image.png\" style=\"width: 115px; height: 129px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0a294475-fd90-4030-96e6-3ac354fb21ba-image.png\" style=\"width: 317px; height: 129px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27006,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{OH}) \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_3$","$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}$","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Sb5owZQ131ErYaTPLxppQR3eNPQdBSJ1prbIARxBmgA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","$\\mathrm{PhCHOHCH}_3$"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":26954,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6f9769a2-37cc-41c7-8d61-c8187b9e52a1-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 128px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4058d472-1e25-43b7-a089-c8f4594f60de-image.png\" style=\"width: 360px; height: 144px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/451c822d-de90-463f-acfa-bae36aa9ecc2-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 138px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/846a81bc-adbf-47d8-8d33-5797f3b2eba3-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 110px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"Initial reaction is Reimer -Tiemann&nbsp;reaction, which gives salicylaldehyde. Which will undergo cross Cannizzaro reaction followed by hydrolysis.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0c4b7a8a-2956-4d5c-ade8-7426720501d8-image.png\" style=\"width: 460px; height: 183px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d953e177-6645-45f0-b5e5-a70ac9ef2c61-image.png\" style=\"width: 460px; height: 193px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a671c41e-7258-4956-a9e9-f7abee24d82c-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 150px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27012,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["alcohols having resonance structures","inter-molecular hydrogen bonding in ethers","inter-molecular hydrogen bonding in alcohols","dipolar character of ethers"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":26952,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"A reacts with <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> , so it should have acidic hydrogen. This implies that the compound will be terminal alkyne. <br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a0e80b7b-0202-4996-8055-c57e318e89a3-image7.png\"> <br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ddcf1f58-5b25-4b5a-ac45-26dfc9d1b342-image8.png\">","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26971,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qwrhmbiwusndfwkmelnimqlipsgnfcudyvqimczmdcvxislkty.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ryhuzgldkqmtansmgkvumtyfzkqyismxxzjbumvttpdrkupidz.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nowcdsreqxolrosuponxohzpvnwxucypqchekhuqeoqxhumdsq.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gstssyvxcsqvgykhstevgykeduzggbfngrhiucuezogczlzbtl.jpeg\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In the first step hydrogen&nbsp;iodide attacks the ether according to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;mechanism and in the second step&nbsp;hydrogen&nbsp;iodide attacks the ether according to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;mechanism.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f311322b-b353-439f-be50-8d8eba5fe446-4ca8ddf6-6360-4944-8142-f0a943ca3581-07cfdce1-ecf7-4edf-a02d-081ff94a23c9-84.jpg\" style=\"width: 498px; height: 237px;\" /><br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":26816,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"When phenol is treated with dilute $\\text{HNO}_3$ at $298\\text{ K}$, it undergoes electrophilic aromatic substitution to give a mixture of ortho-nitrophenol and para-nitrophenol.<br><br>The mixture is separated by steam distillation. Ortho-nitrophenol is steam volatile due to intramolecular hydrogen bonding, whereas para-nitrophenol is not steam volatile due to intermolecular hydrogen bonding. Thus, the steam volatile compound (X) is ortho-nitrophenol.<br><br>Molecular formula of phenol: $\\text{C}_6\\text{H}_6\\text{O}$<br>Molar mass of phenol $= (6 \\times 12) + (6 \\times 1) + 16 = 94\\text{ g mol}^{-1}$<br>Percentage of oxygen in phenol $= \\dfrac{16}{94} \\times 100 \\approx 17.02\\%$<br><br>Molecular formula of ortho-nitrophenol (X): $\\text{C}_6\\text{H}_5\\text{NO}_3$<br>Molar mass of ortho-nitrophenol $= (6 \\times 12) + (5 \\times 1) + 14 + (3 \\times 16) = 139\\text{ g mol}^{-1}$<br>Percentage of oxygen in ortho-nitrophenol $= \\dfrac{48}{139} \\times 100 \\approx 34.53\\%$<br><br>Increase in percentage of oxygen $= 34.53\\% - 17.02\\% = 17.51\\%$<br><br>We need to express this as $y \\times 10^{-1} \\%$.<br>$17.51\\% = 175.1 \\times 10^{-1} \\%$<br><br>Rounding to the nearest integer, we get $175$.<br><br>Answer: $175$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26991,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["glycol/$\\mathrm{LiAlH}_4 / \\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$","glycol/ $\\mathrm{NaH} / \\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$","$\\mathrm{LiAlH}_4$","$\\mathrm{NaBH}_4$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aKQB5rQvomgeICdDsWW7QCJ12AIs7NKz2oZgmR04SQA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null}]